reviews.review_text:
Why Bruce...why? I don't think I will ever forgive Hornsby for taking out the accordion during the baby blues.  I could stand when he did it in the first sets but...for the encore, especially after a great show, you were always hoping for something heavy, and that is what Baby Blue was.  Maybe even Dylan himself would say Garcia did the definitive version of this song...he did say that about Hendrix's version of Watchtower.  Bruce was such a beautiful piano player and could have added something to this song but instead, unforgivably, he detracted from it.  I'll take a '94 version over any '91 versions for this reason alone.  I remember the glares he would get and to this day, it still makes me mad to hear that awful, carnivalistic sounding crap coming out of that decrepit, agonizingly dreadful instrument.
Good clean board.
Dstone5553@aol.com

All about Terrapin Strong Bruce show all around.  Not the best out there, but a great-sounding show nonetheless.  Pretty standard first set highlighted with energetic slide guitar on Minglewood, trading lyrical licks on Maggie's Farm (a song they so loved to play with Bruce), and a tight Picasso.  The centerpiece of the second set is obviously Terrapin Station, but Playing and UJB set it up nicely.  Jam out of Terrapin is nice Jerry/Bruce interplay with plenty of Phil too(!).  A Stella Blue for the ages before the always too-short Bobby Lovelight.  I'll have to agree I'm not a big fan of the accordion in general, and it doesn't fit with the mood of Baby Blue in particular.  That said, it was a nice introspective end the night.
- There are no real good recordings of this show yet; very good first set, worth sitting down & listening if a better tape comes along.
